oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Newfoundland Music and its Influences
oai_dc:dc.dc:subject: Mariposa Folk Festival--folk music
Mariposa Folk Festival--folk music--Area 3--13:30-14:30
oai_dc:dc.dc:description: Sligo Maids Lament -- Sally Gardens -- The Long Slander Sally -- Jenny's chicken -- [Introduction] / Margaret Bennett Knight. -- Jim Harris / (Pat and Joe Bryne). -- McBain / (Rufus Gunichard). -- {Unknown song] / ( Lucy Cormier and Margaret Bennett Knight). -- As I Rolled Out / (Pat and Joe Bryne). -- [Discussion] / Pat and Joe Bryne. -- The Centennial Highway? / Rufus Gunichard. -- The Road to the Isle / (Frank MacArthur). -- [Unknown song] / (Lucy Cormier). -- [Introduction] / Margaret Bennett Knight. -- Lady Lorisle / trad. (Lucy Cormier). -- [Unknown song] - trad. (Margaret Bennet Knight). -- The Rocks of Merasheen / (Pat and Joe Byrne).

Workshop- tunes that everyone knows. Irish music- Donegal's, "Sligo Maids Lament" "Sally Gardens" "The Long Slander Sally" "Jenny's chicken (4th song) . 1st song fiddles the only song that played. At 9:00 minutes in switches to a different recording. Item consists of an audio recording of 'Newfoundland Music and It Influences' hosted by Margard Bennett Knight. Margaret Bennett Knight introduces the other musicians who include Lucy Cormier (french family), Frank MacArthur (Gaelic, dance accordion), Rufus Gunichard (french family -fiddle), Pat and Joe Bryne (Irish background). Pat and Joe Bryne -song called "Jim Harris" shipwreck song- about a captain the skipper of the boat was named Jim Harris- both singing just vocals no instrumental component. Rufus- fiddle tune- "McBain". A milling song with Lucy and Margaret and the rest of the group- the song in 1/2 Gaelic 1/2 eng- the whole group joins in with each others choruses- lucy sings her chorus in french. Pat (one of them is singing the song- not sure which one) " As I Rolled Out" song just vocals not instrument. Joe- speak about traditional Newfoundland music - (also known as Chin Music/mouth music)both he and Pat sing together example of this type of traditional music and (hum didle de ) and they bring in lyrics.. before just sounds like a tone or hum (didle de dum) they are singing together. Rufus- fiddle- self composed tune "The Centennial Highway?" . Frank- tune on the accordion- " The Road to the Isle" Scottish tune. Lucy- singing french song no title provided- about broken heart- no instruments. (continue at 34.42). This item consists of Margaret Bennett Knight hosting a workshop about the music of Newfoundland and its influences, beginning with Lucy Cormier performing an a cappella ballad, "Lady Lorisle"? (trad.), Margaret Bennet Knight performing a song in Gaelic (mouth music) (trad.) at 05:10, and Pat and Joe Byrne performing "The Rocks of Merasheen" at 07:58.
